The Bakala tenant: warm with coal stoves and sign a higher rent
The man, aged and retiring, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "carbon magnet" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of rentals in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his daughter's, and his son's, who is serving sentence.
The three of them have just caught the liberalisation of the rentals.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room floor with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, there is no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler", he shows with his finger the man in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half angry, half resigned.
The BytyOKD.cz Civil Association, which qualified the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends tenants who do not sign the new contracts and who wait until 7 December, the date on which it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, the man only makes a magnet.
"Anything says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large testing laboratory for liberalisation.
After New Year it will occur with the great majority of the apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated lease.
That is why Aksuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG miner waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to you is a number pickup machine.
"To rent 2011", you can read in a light button of your touch screen.
When you pulsate it, a paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost doesn't give time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Shortly thereafter, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the tenants bozones of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase in the rental of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window is opened at the customer service centre for the new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting," the workers who are present in it, after having hesitated briefly, respond when the customer presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old floors for Bakala miners are the most delicate themes in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of Parliament, from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, from ČSSD, had already dealt with them and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Fifty years later I want a new floor."
"I didn't even change the damn toilet dish," the man mentioned in the introduction was unburdened.
According to the workers, for the moment they come more than anything retired to check whether they receive a discount in the rental if they sign in time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
They shall also receive half of the rent discount in February of the remaining tenants who sign the new contract before 15 December.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" is certainly not able to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked for the rental in 2011 about forty-fifty people," says the employee of the window.
In the meantime, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts where necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on rental, the matter shall be settled by an independent judge.
