"The current rentals do not even cover the necessary amounts for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the company's residential portfolio RPG Byty, who adds that the neglected state of the community's fund that angers the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason to increase the rental.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments 4 billion, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 million.
The large screen that hangs from the roof, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of GDP properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most 7.50 Czech crowns per square metre", it is indicated on the screen.
Only 38% increase the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low quantities of 19.66 crowns per square metre," says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rental will remain unchanged the next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not affect rents at all, but will be scaled from four to eight years.
In addition, add the following commitment: the company will invest all the rental raise money (see graph) again on the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Those who sign the lease agreement will have priority.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides in his interior a small nursery with everything itself at such facilities: colour walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose study came out of numerous known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardy.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Designs to his workers in the framework of his social programme.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with child care.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the operational programme on human resources and employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a provision of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guardy running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed to the Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The day-to-day day care centre currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a mini-guardian, it can only simultaneously accommodate a maximum of five children, even though with shifts more during the day.
The operation of the daycare facility is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the daycare centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
While it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guardian programme are comparable to the usual pre-school education programme.
In it, children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach up to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their place of work.
Thus, parents are more productive as they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is one of the sign companies that offers a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The bone house continues fascinating after 100 years. Watch Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the premises called it "the house of the bones."
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that recalls the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with unique lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, one sees a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thoughted order.
At night, the whole façade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twist of the forms continues to surprise us also inside it.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the balconies, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
La Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on bringing down the previous building and starting from zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the House Batlló, made up of several apartments, did not design it by Antoni Gaudí alone.
In the design he collaborated with the architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, in their plans of the project there were ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
In the façade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Park Güell de Gaudí, in which other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the premises shortly after their completion called it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the woods."
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious reasons.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not at all respect the building rules of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although clearly the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impressed with the result it requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public steel.
The arrangements were never done, rather, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the town council application, Josep Batlló requested (and got) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented into a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can thus communicate without any problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and slots.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
