Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private enterprises.
Crime generates greater concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a country that is more influential than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it allows for monitoring of changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related issues are highlighted in the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the relatively animated mood reigning in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a reduced of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Graph 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but significantly higher than 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has been maintained during the global financial crisis is probably because many Latin American countries have only been affected by a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in conditions of poverty is only marginally increasing in 2009 and has declined again this year to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the start of the surveys, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, such as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent claims that they or a close relative have been the victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has been reduced since 38% last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in increased support for private companies and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see Figure 6).
About 58 per cent agrees that the market economy is the only system that will allow its country to develop, compared with 47 per cent last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% supports private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country that has greater leadership in the region, as it indicates 19 per cent of respondents (compared to 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by the respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela bears this title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
