"This body has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it a very peculiar thing, although little is missing to be a really 'alien' way of life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in the online edition of Thursday of the publication Science.
For a long time, there have been six major elements that are essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have found that the bacterium, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what more is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
As Anbar pointed out, finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbio discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated a great speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report indicating the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "shows it is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider essential for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor of Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, at Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it shows the substitution of one element for another in the biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's astrobiology institute, which led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so it speculated that a microbes exposed to both could replace one by another.
"Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Consequently, it can be complicated for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, the arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work as well as the phosphorus, so it comes in and, in some ways, it calls the biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
Researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbial grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that it can exist naturally a form of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an auxiliary professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example that proves it works.
The arsenic was more common in the early Earth's eras, he said, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life could have used it.
"Yes, he suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past," Foster said, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Institutes.
