Avengant hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy governing relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound international changes and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (independently from the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential for the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grial, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Temples or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for new facts about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they have already learned.
This is Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to secret records.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), which only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sending the U.S. embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as that published the Newsweek the week before.
Why, then, have the revelations of these records caused such a revolution?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of States can call themselves by phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become spy centres.
Any viewer who sees research films knows perfectly, we just pretend we don't know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both victims and "verdugues".
But we enter the true nature of what has happened.
Previously, in Orwell's day, he could be conceived of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The prophecy of Orwell has come true since, having been able to control each movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction performed, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as now happens, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the vengeful citizen) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that cannot even retain its own secrets be endured?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power from him.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like to publish it on a road map.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, confidential telephone conversations cannot be expected.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has moved on a plane and has contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they maintain in the future private and confidential relations?
I know perfectly well that for the time being, my prediction is science fiction and, therefore, newscast, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, as much, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
This information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked boxes: in the end, the spy attempt of Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is now advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digital) only allow to advance or retreat from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that communication policies and techniques bring us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly going on in the embassies.
The embassies are currently asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s caps on its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider whether the fast-tracked funding promises (called fast start or early ones) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French carpets have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to providing EUR 7.200 million in three years and France EUR 1.260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was a remarkable result and was appreciated for what really was worth: the developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 EUR 2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment to EUR 7.200 million in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has made reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years in terms of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or at the level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" for 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the costs of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of aid from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the split between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider each euro to be equivalent to a euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on the most effective technologies), it is a mistake to present a euro which is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, only the cost of the loan to the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent to a interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find this reasoning useful: "respect" its commitment of EUR 420 million making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to meet its commitment, France only gives ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Good trick!
In short, in its fast start funding, France commits double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending just €36.1 million, you can give the impression that you spend 420 million "new and additional", as you promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems to be Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give when they can simply lend?) as in the negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a minute, relative to the short-term, in relation to the whole climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward discussions on betting in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive in relation to this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement on the fast start of France and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
